          I think I figured out why FSEVN went to the Tom Jones concert.  The other day, he mentioned that he had a mountain of work and almost jumped out a window, when he remembered a certain WWDC.  Clearly, this was a typo, and he meant "WWJD";  What Would Jesus Do?  Well, Jesus would do what any good soul would do, which is to go to the Tom Jones concert.  Knowing this, FSEVN knew that he, too, should be in attendance.  Also, he really likes "What's New Pussycat".<br /><br />Also, I'm sorry to hear about your unnoticed birthday, FSEVN.  I'm sure Jesus remembered it.  My 20th birthday is today though, and since you haven't called, you can't be mad at me for not calling you.  <br /><br />Dear Tuuk,<br />I disagree with your calling "Dark Side of the Moon" the greatest album of all time.  With regards to certain aspects of popluarity or sales, it may be, but I think that calling it the greatest album of all time might be a bit presumptuous.<br /><br />Also, I'm not sure I understand your saying that Western music is not typically mathematical while Eastern music is.  As I understand, and please, correct me if I'm wrong, today's system of 12 notes and their relationships (known as "equal temperament") is based on the octave (doubling of frequency, as in a "C" up to the next closest "C") being split into 12 equal intervals called half-steps (the smallest practical interval).  The relationships of the frequencies of sequential half-steps are based on an exponential scale... anyway, I'm usually too much of a dunce to understand this stuff well enough to truly explain it, but it works out that a half-step above one note's frequency is the 12th root of 2 (about 1.0595) larger.  Following this sequence, 5 half-steps (a perfect 4th) vibrates at a ratio of about 4:3 with the tonic (original) pitch, just as 7 half-steps (a perfect 5th) is about a 3:2 ratio, and 12 half-steps (a perfect octave) vibrates at a ratio of exactly 2:1.  What this means, I believe, is that some pitch intervals (such as these "perfect" intervals) are naturally more harmonious because of the closeness of these relationships... umm... that is to say, that 3:2 is more easy on the ears than the square root of 2:1 (a tritone).  So, yeah, I just kind of confused myself, because I really didn't write that in an entirely coherent manner.  Do with it what ye will, anyway.  <br /><br />Sorry for the drawn-outedness of this post.  Me go sleepy-sleep now.<br />
