     <font class="TallRed">My birthday celebration and/or the lack thereof.<a name="108779063442127990">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          <img src="http://www.thebroadwaycollection.com/images/shows/12/showpic_12.jpg" hspace="3" align="right">Well, it's Sunday and boy am I ready for some hardcore sleepin' action. My birthday was on Friday and Morg and I went to see STOMP at Richmond's Landmark Theatre. It was totally awesome. The beats were right up my alley. It was like...industrial techno without the computers. When Morgan asked me how I liked it my official response was "I have never been so entertained in my life." Very cool show, if any of you have any extra cash at the given time that STOMP is performing in your area, go check it out. <br /><br />In other entertaining news, none of my family members called me on my birthday. I found this so funny that I decided to start calling <i>them</i>. All I got was voicemail and even then, I never got a response until the next day. <i>Glad to see you people are on top of things, thanks!</i> I didn't even want anything except for a "happy birthday" from the people who were responsible for it. But, no deal. My mom said, "you know me, son. I was too busy, sorry!" and my dad said, "I was going to call you...but I fell asleep instead." My uncle, the one that I'm staying with right now for this internship had no clue that my birthday was on Friday and was still confused as to which day it was on until I came back tonight and cleared it up for him. I had to use my own money for dinner (except for what morgan bought me in pity [thanks morgan!] and now the money that I spent I owe to <i>myself</i> due to lack of funds and the required money for costly gas and metro tickets. <br /><br />After the show, we picked up some <a href="http://www.blogger.com/profile/3586520">friends</a> around the area and would have had more but a certain <a href="http://www.blogger.com/profile/3571803">two</a> <a href="http://www.blogger.com/profile/3571753">significants</a> weren't in town. We went to Denny's for dinner which was fine with me and soon called it a night. Morgan was sick most of the weekend so she wasn't having as much fun as she could have had but went with the flow of things anyway. <blockquote><b>Things that must be frowned upon this weekend:</b> parking tickets, gas prices, friends who call you when you're in town just to get a ride to some place. All equally annoying. And if you reading this and you're responsible for any of these things, go pat yourself on the back, ass.<br /><b>Things that must be smiled upon this weekend:</b> families that enjoy you more than your own, playing guitar with skilled drummer, eating enough 'complimentary birthday dessert dishes' to make Dr. Phil go into a seizure.</blockquote> By the way, when I'm talking about "family" I'm talkin intermediate family not my ultra-fabulous-adopted-aunt/uncle family. Confused? Get used to it, and no, I don't live in West Virginia. <br />
          <div class="byline">
<b>jd.b!</b>&nbsp;@ 11:34 PM [<a href="http://www.devlogik.com/www/E3R_2/blog/2004/06/my-birthday-celebration-andor-lack.php" title="permanent link">#</a>|<a href="mailto:devlogik@gmail.com?subject=RE: E3R POST #108779063442127990&body=Hey jd.b!!">e</a>|<a href="http://www.devlogik.com/www/E3R_2/blog/2004/06/my-birthday-celebration-andor-lack.php">2.</a>cmnt(s)]</div>
		</div><br>


     
     
     <font class="TallRed">Vibrations in the Air<a name="108771468101426574">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          I've decided that I need to rekindle my interest in music, just really relearn to love it.  In doing so, I've realized that I don't - I can't - care about whether or not what I listen to is popular, or "good", or anything like that.  I am very much in agreement with Tuuk about music as having some sort of ineffable ability to move a particluar person, even while leaving others unaffected.  Alas, as a student of music, I've been trained to not accept certain configurations of sound as being music (I just tried to explain to a friend a few weeks ago why certain sound combinations are mathematically undesirable), or well-written music at the very least.  But, dammit, it's downright discouraging to hear someone tell you that something you feel very influenced by is crap, and I hear it all the time.  I hate that, and I have to actively catch myself from doing it sometimes.  Music should be a subjective thing, and everyone should probably stop trying to simplify or quantify it.<br /><br />I've kind of always thought this way, and now I'm just reassuring myself in saying this.  I believe it was a man by the name of Marshall Mathers who once said, "You think I give a damn about a Grammy?"  Who cares what's popular?  An hour or two ago I played through Vivaldi's "L'Inverno (winter) Concerto";  Will mainstream America request it for the Top 40 with Casey Kasem?  Not a chance, but I request it.  I like it, and it makes me happy.<br /><br />I'm not trying to be insensitive to other people's choices in music, and what music makes them happy, I'm just saying that what makes one body happy may not work for another.  And now I'm going to work some more on my remix of Europe's "Final Countdown", and you're not going to say anything about it.<br />
          <div class="byline">
<b>KevinRules</b>&nbsp;@ 2:10 AM [<a href="http://www.devlogik.com/www/E3R_2/blog/2004/06/vibrations-in-air.php" title="permanent link">#</a>|<a href="mailto:KevRhodes@gmail.com?subject=RE: E3R POST #108771468101426574&body=Hey KevinRules!">e</a>]</div>
		</div><br>


     
     
     <font class="TallRed">bad music!  bad!<a name="108771194516755630">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          Is the music industry really in such a sad state these days, as some people claim it is?<br /><br />That all depends on how you look at it.<br /><br />Turn on the radio, turn on MTV, flip through a copy of Rollingstone, and you'll most likely only see and here slosh that all sounds pretty much the same.  Videos of scantilly clad super models shaking their round patooshes while a "tru thug" raps only about sex and money, guys in their 30's whining through their nose about a highschool break up, a guy in a cowboy hat bragging about his pickup truck and the number of beers he tossed back the night before:  this is corporate rock.  This is popular because of the whole "do what worked well in the past" method.  As mentioned in an earlier post, this started almost as soon as rock started (monkees playing like the beatles).  In the past 10 years, this method has become used to such an extent, that its damn near impossible to find any original, true alternative music(otherwise known as good music) without turning off your radio or mtv.  It's all an unfortunate byproduct of capitalism and media merging.  For example, i'm sure most of you have heard of Clear Channel, a company that owns the majority of all the radio stations IN THE WORLD.  Their ideology, being a monopoly and all, is to make as much money as possible while bumping off all competition.  What's popular in one region will be popular in another region, and every region, to infinite; that is, if their radio stations force it down your throat for long enough.  This is why you turn on a rock station somewhere on the west coast and it sounds exactly the same as a rock station on the east coast.<br /><br />What worries me about this, as stated somewhere above, is the general message that seems to be found in all the music that populates the airwaves these days: that of superficiality and materialsim.  Lets face it: kids like whatever older people tell them are cool.  When they see Jay-z on MTV telling us how cool it is to be a pimp and make money, they're getting the wrong message.  Christina Aguileria bumping around practically naked and humping the camera while 11 year old girls take notes.  There doesnt seem to be any substance in this type of music.  Their messages are appallingly shallow.  And this is what the younger generation is being raised on.  I mean, when i was 12, i watched hours of MTV a day.  I was fortunate enough to have grown up though when mainstream music actually meant something more than trying to get laid (or complaining about not getting laid, for all you emo kids).  <br /><br />This is not saying that these kids won't ever see past this veil the music industry has thrown across our impressionable young faces; afterall, classic rock stations are still fairly decent, and that right there is the stepping stone to hoist your way out of the corporate rock abyss.  And there are certainly lots of great modern bands out there, with lyrics that actually, *gasp*, make you think.  And there is hope.  <br /><br />My point is: To get to the good stuff, you have to find your way through all the bad stuff.  And as thick as the wall of mainstream music is today, i fear that younger generations may never discover bands like Joy Division, The Smiths, and Radiohead.<br /><br />Thats all for now.<br />
          <div class="byline">
<b>paranoidandroid</b>&nbsp;@ 1:25 AM [<a href="http://www.devlogik.com/www/E3R_2/blog/2004/06/bad-music-bad.php" title="permanent link">#</a>|<a href="mailto:bigd4587@aol.com?subject=RE: E3R POST #108771194516755630&body=Hey paranoidandroid!">e</a>]</div>
		</div><br>


     
     
